{"text": " What would happen if the sun disappeared? At first, nothing. We'd keep orbiting that empty spot. We're so far away that its final rays would take 8 minutes and 20 seconds to reach us. And then, darkness. We can't even see the moons since it only shines from reflected sunlight within a year of the surface is frozen. Earth's core is still hot, so maybe life survives for a while, deep down in the ocean near a hydrothermal vent. But the scariest part is what would happen to the sun's gravity. At that same 8-minute and 22nd mark, it would disappear. Because gravity travels at the speed of light. So the moment that darkness hits is also the moment we go flying off into space. What if the moon disappears? To find out, follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 2.88, "text": " What would happen if the sun disappeared?", "tokens": [50364, 708, 576, 1051, 498, 264, 3295, 13954, 30, 50508], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13380517381610293, "compression_ratio": 1.6217105263157894, "no_speech_prob": 0.008590538054704666}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 2.88, "end": 4.4, "text": " At first, nothing.", "tokens": [50508, 1711, 700, 11, 1825, 13, 50584], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13380517381610293, "compression_ratio": 1.6217105263157894, "no_speech_prob": 0.008590538054704666}, {"id": 2, "seek": 0, "start": 4.4, "end": 6.5600000000000005, "text": " We'd keep orbiting that empty spot.", "tokens": [50584, 492, 1116, 1066, 48985, 300, 6707, 4008, 13, 50692], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13380517381610293, "compression_ratio": 1.6217105263157894, "no_speech_prob": 0.008590538054704666}, {"id": 3, "seek": 0, "start": 6.5600000000000005, "end": 11.28, "text": " We're so far away that its final rays would take 8 minutes and 20 seconds to reach us.", "tokens": [50692, 492, 434, 370, 1400, 1314, 300, 1080, 2572, 24417, 576, 747, 1649, 2077, 293, 945, 3949, 281, 2524, 505, 13, 50928], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1338